Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and was actively involved in educating the natives, education in South West Africa was largely left to missionary societies with minimal government backing. However, the government did allocate considerable resources to the education of Europeans in the colony, setting up state schools and providing more substantial support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational strategies left a lasting impact on South West Africa, persisting even after the end of German rule. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to the distinct experience of South West Africa. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors and focus on new research concerning the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a substantial body of literature focused specifically on education within the German colonial empire. Most of these works are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The primary goal of these early writings was to describe the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language publications broadened the discussion through comparative studies of educational practices across different German colonies and more in-depth analyses of specific educational aspects. These studies highlighted significant variations in the educational systems across different colonies. One of the most notable works that explicitly addresses the subject of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of these two colonies and explores the factors that explain the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounts for many of the distinctive characteristics of the colony’s educational system.

Compared to Germany’s other colonial holdings, South West Africa had a relatively temperate climate, although much of it consisted of arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, whereas the next largest settler population was in East Africa, with only 5,336 Europeans.

The United States and Mexico serve as an example of two countries that were once embroiled in a long-lasting rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, eventually subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry was fueled by clashes over key issues such as religion, culture, tradition, and significant material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This situation is similar to many other countries with enduring rivalries with neighboring nations. Countries sharing a border often have conflicting interests that lead to rivalries. The United States and Mexico exemplify such enduring border rivalries. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both countries are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, whereas other Latin American nations have generally maintained good relations with the U.S.

Religious differences were a significant source of tension between the two countries, a problem that has historically affected many nations. Sally Frahm (2001) observes that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Similar to the ideological and interest-based Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, the U.S.-Mexico tensions were rooted in religious preferences rather than political structures. This mistrust stemmed from the historical distrust between the English and Spanish, which both countries inherited from their colonial rulers, hindering the development of positive foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this 57-year period of rivalry. Most of these disputes revolved around territorial issues, particularly border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier challenges. Raids by bandits and outlaws on American border towns persisted until both nations asserted military force along their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and eventually ended as American priorities shifted "from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p. 110) in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I unexpectedly became disabled due to an illness I had never heard of before. At that time, I was working as a nurse, a career I chose because it offered the stability and security I lacked during my childhood. The advice I frequently heard growing up was, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." Although my true aspiration was to be a scientist or journalist, or perhaps both, I opted for nursing.

However, at 46, I found myself single, without savings, and unable to work. Even now, after 15 years on Social Security Disability, I have nothing to my name. I manage to get by, but each day is a battle affecting my sense of safety, security, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is predictable anymore, I do know one thing: I couldn't have survived these years without the support of my family and a few close friends. In times of true crisis, no matter how strong you think you are, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that life will always have emergencies, both big and small, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some challenges are too significant to handle alone. I agree that in the U.S., we should stop relying solely on big government, which is deteriorating. Instead, I would prefer Americans to learn to trust and support one another, rather than each person retreating to build their own fallout shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. often speak of "rugged individualism" as the foundation of our country, but in reality, what sustained our ancestors during tough times was compassion, mutual respect, and resource-sharing. The pioneers who traveled in wagon trains across the Rockies didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights, a variety of batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have land and resources for a small farm and the ability to preserve your own food, do it. It's a smart idea, as is having a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while doing all this, take the time to get to know your neighbors.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince destined to be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he gave up worldly possessions, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings eventually led to the creation of Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being its most traditional branch. Buddhism is approximately 2,500 years old, and it has evolved since the time of Buddha, evident in practices like the annual water-cutting ceremony in Theravada Buddhist Sri Lanka. This event, involving both monks and laypeople, holds religious significance, even though Buddha never mentioned such celebrations. Variations span from minor traditions to the fundamental beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both monastic and lay, has had to adapt its doctrines over time due to both internal and external influences, some of which were supportive and others adversarial.

Several key terms are frequently used in this discussion. Internal forces originate from within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic involvement, while external forces arise from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces aim to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from negative views of Buddhism, whereas benign forces neither intend to harm nor help Buddhism, although they may inadvertently do so. These terms recur throughout the discourse.

To begin, one must understand the fundamentals of the religion—the central doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka or three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka includes all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains Buddhism's metaphysical aspects. These metaphysical ideas include Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—life’s inherent suffering, and Anicca—the impermanence of all things. Understanding these concepts is essential to ending Sansara, the ongoing cycle of death and rebirth. With the cessation of Sansara comes the end of lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, upon reaching enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes life rules: for laypeople, the five precepts are refraining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and consuming intoxicants. Monks have additional disciplinary rules. The core doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, Dukkha, the truth that life involves suffering; second, the truth that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
